{"action_type":"wp_patch","wpId":123,"url":"https://liftnow.com/products/vehicle-lifts/","slug":"vehicle-lifts","wp_type":"product_cat","opportunity":"PAGE_2_STRUGGLE","patch":{"title":"Car Lift for Garage: Fleet Vehicle Lifts | Liftnow","excerpt":"Commercial car lifts for municipal and fleet garages. Two-post, four-post, mobile column lifts from 9,000–80,000 lbs GVWR. Sourcewell contract 121223-LFT pricing.","new_h2":"What car lift capacity do I need for a municipal fleet garage?","new_section_body":"Match the lift to your heaviest regular unit, then add 20% headroom. For a typical municipal fleet mixing pickups (6,000–8,500 lbs) and single-axle utility trucks (12,000–16,000 lbs GVWR), a 12,000-lb two-post handles 80% of your bay traffic. Add one 18,000-lb four-post for the heavier Class 4/5 trucks, and you've covered the whole rotation without overbuying capacity you won't use.

If you're running anything Class 6+ (box trucks, bucket trucks, small transit buses in the 20,000–26,000 lb range), you need four-post or mobile column lifts. Across Liftnow's government install base, the most common mistake is spec'ing a 10,000-lb two-post for a fleet that includes even three or four 19,500 GVWR trucks — those units sit in the bay waiting for the one compliant lift, or worse, get serviced on jack stands because the two-post can't safely engage the frame.

Sourcewell contract 121223-LFT covers two-post (9,000–18,000 lbs), four-post (12,000–40,000 lbs), and mobile column sets (60,000–80,000 lbs combined). Send your vehicle list with GVWRs to gov@liftnow.com and we'll spec the minimum lift mix that keeps your entire fleet off the floor. Pricing depends on your bay dimensions and whether you need 220V single-phase or 480V three-phase power, confirmed on the quote."}}
